07198nam a22009375i 9781477319406DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212019txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019007789  a97814773194067 a10.7560/3193832doi  a(DE-B1597)587531  a(OCoLC)1269268502  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aPN1997.85b.C636 2019 4aPN1997.85b.C636 2019 7aLIT0000002bisacsh00aComics and Pop Culture :bAdaptation from Panel to Frame /ced. by Barry Keith Grant, Scott Henderson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (330 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE ISSUES AND DEBATES -- tThe Crossroads of Infinity, or Universum Incognitum -- tFrom Adaptation to Extension: A History of Comics Adapting Films, 1974–2015 -- tTake the Movie Home! How the Comic Book Tie-In Anticipated Transmedia Production -- tManga, Anime, Adaptation: Economic Strategies, Aesthetic Specificities, Social Issues -- tGenre and Superhero Cinema -- tDestroying the Rainbow Bridge: Representations of Heterosexuality in Marvel Superhero Narratives -- tMutatis Mutandis: Constructing Fidelity in the Comic Book Film Adaptation -- t“We Roller Coaster Through . . . ” : Screenwriting, Narrative Economy, and the Inscription of the Haptic in Tentpole Comic Book Movies -- tAdaptation and Seriality: Comic Book to Television Series Adaptations -- tPART TWO PANELS AND FRAMES -- tFelix in—and out of—Space -- tA Comic Book Life/Style: World Building in American Splendor -- tThe Extraordinary Career of Modesty Blaise -- tAuthenticity and Judge Dredd on Film -- tCGI as Adaptation Strategy: Can a Digitally Constructed Spider-Man Do Whatever a Hand-Drawn Spider-Man Can? -- tScott Pilgrim’s Precious Little Texts: Adaptation, Form, and Transmedia Co-creation -- tTransmedia Adaptation and Writing in the Margins: A Graphic Expansion of George Romero’s Night of the Living Dead -- tAgency and Intertextuality: Tank Girl, Subcultural Aesthetics, and the Strong Female Protagonist -- tBlack Panther: Aspiration, Identification, and Appropriation -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is hard to discuss the current film industry without acknowledging the impact of comic book adaptations, especially considering the blockbuster success of recent superhero movies. Yet transmedial adaptations are part of an evolution that can be traced to the turn of the last century, when comic strips such as “Little Nemo in Slumberland” and “Felix the Cat” were animated for the silver screen. Representing diverse academic fields, including technoculture, film studies, theater, feminist studies, popular culture, and queer studies, Comics and Pop Culture presents more than a dozen perspectives on this rich history and the effects of such adaptations. Examining current debates and the questions raised by comics adaptations, including those around authorship, style, and textual fidelity, the contributors consider the topic from an array of approaches that take into account representations of sexuality, gender, and race as well as concepts of world-building and cultural appropriation in comics from Modesty Blaise to Black Panther. The result is a fascinating re-imagination of the texts that continue to push the boundaries of panel, frame, and popular culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aComic books, strips, etcxFilm adaptations. 0aComic books, strips, etc.xFilm adaptations. 0aComic strip characters in motion pictures. 0aComic strip characters on television. 0aFilm adaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aMass media and culture. 0aMotion pictures